Inputs\: command - executes ValidateCloneOracleHome.py Instance Wrapper - The jython call wrapper required to run as the oracle user. New Oracle Home Names - Comma separated list of Oracle Home Names. There must be one New Oracle Home Name for each New Oracle Home. New Oracle Homes - Comma separated list of fully qualified Oracle Homes that will be cloned (copied) from the Oracle Homes list. There must be one New Oracle Home for each Oracle Home Oracle Homes - Comma separated list of fully qualified Oracle Homes to clone (copy). One or more is required. Oracle Inventory Info - Dictionary list of all information discovered in the supplied inventory file(s). host - Target to run this command against password - Login information for host username - Login information for host protocol - ssh/wmi timeout - Time (ms) before auto-exit\: use ${ExtendedTimeout} to lengthen. Results\: Clone Oracle Home Names - Comma separated list of Oracle Home Names of the Cloned Homes. Clone Oracle Homes - Comma separated list of fully qualified pathnames of the Oracle homes to Clone. Node List - Jython list of nodes to clone. Oracle Homes - Comma separated list of fully qualified pathnames of the Oracle Homes. Exit Code - Exit code of the step needed for branching. 64241782-e80d-4e10-be97-a11bca6f9fb3.4c69c172-e147-4f4a-87e9-50880ccc6bfe.description=Description\: This step parses the Oracle inventory files that exists, or else it forwards the inventory information. (1) If the inventory pointer files are specified and exist, parse these files extracting the contents. (2) If and inventory file is specified and does not exist, ensure a valid specification. (3) If no inventory file is specified, assign the appropriate default. Dependencies\: Must run as the server superuser. Return Code\: 0 \= All files were found on the system. 1 \= Errors occured while checking files. Inputs\: command - executes ParseOracleInventory.py Inventory Files - Optional\: Comma-separated list of fully-qualified Oracle inventory files. If this parameter is not specified, the workflow looks for the oraInst.loc file in /etc and /var/opt/oracle. Oracle Account - Optional\: Oracle user that will own the Oracle Home. This is required only if inventory does not exist. Oracle Home - Optional\: The ORACLE_HOME to use if more than one Home is in the inventory file(s). Server Wrapper - Required\: String to execute routine as server superuser. Server.Become Routine - No description host - Target to run this command against password - Login information for host username - Login information for host protocol - ssh/wmi timeout - Time (ms) before auto-exit\: use ${ExtendedTimeout} to lengthen. Results\: Cluster Nodes - Comma-separated list of all nodes where the Oracle Home is deployed. CRS Account - The OS owner of the ORA_CRS_HOME. CRS Active Version - The active CRS version. CRS Group - The Oracle group used for the ORA_CRS_HOME installation. CRS Home - The last ORA_CRS_HOME location in the inventory file. CRS Home Name - The name of the ORA_CRS_HOME as recorded in the inventory. CRS Nodes - Comma-separated list of all nodes where the Oracle Clusterware is deployed. Inventory Groups - Comma-separated list of fully-qualified inventory groups. One for each Inventory Pointer. Inventory Locations - Comma-separated list of fully-qualified inventory pathname directories. Inventory Pointers - Comma-separated list of fully-qualified inventory pointer files. Oracle Account - Oracle user that will own the Oracle Home. Oracle Group - The Oracle group used for the ORACLE_HOME installation Oracle Home - The last ORACLE_HOME located in the inventory file or the user-inputted Oracle Home. Oracle Home Info - Dictionary list of all information discovered in the supplied inventory file(s). Oracle Home Name - The name of the ORACLE_HOME as recorded in the inventory. Oracle Listener Account - The OS owner of the ORACLE_HOME of the relevant listener. Oracle Version - Version of the Oracle Home. SQLPlus Version - Version of SQLPlus from Oracle Home. Clone Oracle Homes - Comma separated list of fully qualified pathnames of the Oracle Homes to Clone. Instance Wrapper - String to execute routine as instance superuser. Inventory Pointer - Fully qualified pathname of oracle inventory pointer file. Node List - List of nodes with the Oracle Home to patch. Clone the local machine with the value ['localhost']. Oracle Homes - Comma separated list of fully qualified pathnames of the Oracle Homes to update. host - Target to run this command against password - Login information for host username - Login information for host protocol - ssh/wmi timeout - Time (ms) before auto-exit\: use ${ExtendedTimeout} to lengthen. Results\: Cloned Homes - Comma separated list of fully qualified pathnames of the Clones Oracle Homes. Exit Code - Exit code of the step needed for branching. 64241782-e80d-4e10-be97-a11bca6f9fb3.description=
 Purpose

Make a clone (copy) of an Oracle Home on the same server.


 Description

This workflow Copies an Oracle Home using the tar facility.
This copy of the Oracle Home is then registered in the inventory using the Oracle Installer (runInstaller).
This was originally designed to be used for applying patches and patchsets in conjunction with the _Migrate Oracle Home_ workflow

 Required Inputs

    Server Target - The desired target to run this flow against.
    Server Target Username - The user to login to the Server Target as.
    Server Target Password - The password to login as the Server Target Username.
    Download Source Host - The target host where the files needed for this flow can be downloaded from.
    Download Source Path - The path to where the files can be found on the Download Source Host.
    Instance.os user - No description
    New Oracle Homes - Comma separated list of fully qualified Oracle Homes that will be cloned (copied) from the Oracle Homes list. There must be one New Oracle Home for each Oracle Home
    Oracle Homes - Comma separated list of fully qualified Oracle Homes to clone (copy). One or more is required.
    Server.Become Routine - No description
    Server.Become User - No description

 Optional Inputs

    Clean Code Base - Remove code base from target after execution (True || False).
    Clean JRE - Remove JRE from target after execution (True || False).
    Debug Level - Set level of output [(least) 1-5 (most)]
    Inventory Files - Optional\: Comma-separated list of fully-qualified Oracle inventory files. If this parameter is not specified, the workflow looks for the oraInst.loc file in /etc and /var/opt/oracle.

 Dependencies

\# The workflow must have unchallenged ability to become the server superuser userid (typically _root_).
This is generally done using  _sudo_ or _ssh root@localhost_
\# The workflow must have unchallenged ability to become the oracle database userid (typically _oracle_).
This is generally done using  _sudo_ or _ssh oracle@localhost_




 Additional Documentation

Additional information, including the _HP Database and Middleware Automation Support Matrix_ and solution pack user guides, are available via HP Live Network\:

"http\://hpln.hp.com/group/database-and-middleware-automation"\:http\://hpln.hp.com/group/database-and-middleware-automation

To access the documentation, click the RESOURCES link and enter your HP Passport credentials.
